            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "The rhythmic lurch of the 38-Geary MUNI bus is the metronome of Jonathan Kim\u2019s mornings. For him, the 3.8-mile commute from his Inner Richmond apartment to his SoMa office is a cherished buffer zone\u2014a time to observe the city\u2019s complex human interface before diving into his own work of deciphering it.\n\nJonathan is the son of first-generation Korean immigrants who established a successful dry-cleaning business in Cupertino. Growing up in the shadow of Apple, he was surrounded by tech, but his parents preached a gospel of tangible hard work, not abstract code. They hoped for a doctor or a lawyer; his initial pursuit of a Computer Science degree at UC Davis was a compromise. However, a pivotal elective in cognitive psychology revealed his true calling. He wasn't fascinated by building the machine, but by understanding the person using it. This epiphany led him to a graduate program in Human-Computer Interaction, a field that finally reconciled his analytical mind with his innate empathy.\n\nHis career began at a massive, impersonal ad-tech firm. The work paid well but felt hollow, optimizing clicks to sell products he didn\u2019t care about. The turning point came three years ago when he was laid off during a restructuring. Instead of returning to the corporate grind, he took a significant pay cut to become the Lead UX Researcher for a mid-sized company that builds management software for non-profits. Here, his research on user needs directly helps charities operate more efficiently. It\u2019s a career choice that finally feels aligned with his parents\u2019 values of service, albeit in a thoroughly modern context.\n\nJonathan\u2019s life is anchored in the Inner Richmond. He loves the neighborhood\u2019s foggy microclimate and its proximity to Golden Gate Park, where he goes for long runs. His social circle is a tight-knit group of friends from grad school and a local climbing gym. His partner of four years, Maya, is a public school teacher, and their different worlds provide a healthy balance to his tech-centric profession.\n\nHis future aspirations aren't tied to climbing the corporate ladder. Jonathan dreams of leveraging his skills to launch a passion project: a simple, multi-lingual app designed to help elderly immigrants like his own parents navigate complex civic services and healthcare systems. He sees it as the ultimate UX challenge\u2014using technology not for profit, but to restore dignity and independence. For Jonathan, San Francisco is more than a workplace; it's the perfect, complicated, human-centered problem he feels uniquely equipped to help solve."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nineteen, sitting in a cavernous UC Davis lecture hall, when the professor said, \u201cThe user isn't the problem; the design is.\u201d It felt less like a lecture point and more like a key turning in a complex lock. The abstract frustration of his computer science classes dissolved, replaced by a sudden, intense focus on the human on the other side of the screen. That sentence didn't just change his major; it gave him a mission. He wasn\u2019t meant to build the machine, but to be its conscience.\n\n2.\nThe layoff three years ago was surprisingly quiet. After the canned HR script, Jonathan walked out not into panic, but into the crisp SoMa air. He felt a profound, illicit sense of relief. Walking past the glass towers, he realized he hadn't been building anything, just optimizing emptiness. The loss of that job wasn't an ending but an escape. It was the moment he chose to trade a higher salary for a higher purpose, a decision that finally made him feel like his parents\u2019 son.\n\n3.\nOne foggy Tuesday on the 38-Geary, he watched an elderly Cantonese-speaking woman clutch a confusing transfer slip, her face a mask of quiet anxiety as she missed her stop. Jonathan felt a pang of useless empathy. He knew the system, but he couldn't bridge the gap for her in that moment. The feeling of helplessness galvanized into resolve. By the time he reached his office, the seed of his passion project\u2014an app for people exactly like her, and like his parents\u2014had firmly taken root.\n\n4.\nHe can still summon the smell of steam and perchloroethylene from his parents\u2019 Cupertino shop. He was about fourteen, watching his mother patiently guide a flustered customer through a complex stain issue on a delicate dress. She used simple words and reassuring gestures, her focus entirely on the woman\u2019s concern. He didn\u2019t have the vocabulary for it then, but he now recognizes it as the purest form of user experience: an act of service built on empathy. It's the standard he still strives for in his own work.\n\n5.\nLast winter, he and Maya were curled on the couch, the fog pressing against their apartment window. He was venting about a frustrating user study for the non-profit software, while she was celebrating a student who finally sounded out a difficult word. In that moment, he saw the thread connecting their different worlds. It wasn't about debugging code or grading papers; it was about the small, monumental victory of one person overcoming a barrier. It affirmed that he was exactly where he needed to be, with her."
